{"/service/ndnp/idhi/batch_idhi_irving_ver01/data/sn86091109/00295867942/1908060501/0370.xml":{"full_text":"LEWISTON EVENING TELLER\nMember Associated Press\nDaily Except Sandar\nLewiston Publishing Company, Ltd\nPhone Main 261.\n\u25a0stored at the Lewiston Post office\n\u00dc second class matter.\nSOBflCUPTlOM BATER\nDAILY.\nweek\nthree m ea th s\nSix months\nOae year\n.1 M\nAO\n11.36\n3.60\n6.00\nWEEKLY.\nOne year..................fl.60\nttx months .....'............76\nFour months.................60\nFRIDAY\nJUNE 5, 1908.\nWBATHER REPORT.\nForecast for Lewiston and vicini\nty for tonight and tomorrow\nFollowing oatv nx iro at local\nPair tonight. Saturday fair and\nwarmer.\n\u2022ffioe United St&t^ weatlier bureau\nai 3:30 o'clyek'Anla afternoon:\nMaximum temperature, 71; mini\nmum temperature, 51; mean tem\nperature, 61; precipitation, .02.\nTV, W. THOMAS.\nOfficial in Charge\nDUBOIS STILL VICTORIOUS.\nIt is now made apparent that Du\nbois controlled the Twin Falls con\nvention, that the antis bolted nnd\nthat of the two contesting delega\ntions that will be sent to the na\ntional convention, the one seated\nwill be the Dubois delegation. This\n^does not heal the schism in the dem\nocratlc party, but It leaves ex-Sena\n\u2022ter Dubois In the paramount position\nof being the leader of Idaho democr\nracy and recognized as such by the\nnational convention.\nIt is now known that W. J. Bryan\ntook a hand in shaping matters for\nths Twin Pulls convention and made\na personal appeal to the democrats\nto stand by Senator Dubois and the\nMormon issue. Whatever effect this\nmay have had on the convention,\nthis much is certain, that when the\ncontesting delegations come to Den\nver the fact that Bryan's personal\nsympathies are with the Idaho lead\ner will weigh heavily enough In the\nbalance to cause the seating of the\nDubo'.s delegates and the ousting of\nthe bolters.\nThis ends the first battle. The\nsecond contest Is likely to be pre\ncipitated at the Wallace convention,\nwhere the making of a state plat\nform ahd the nomination of a state\nticket wPl engage the warring\nforces. Senator Dubois suggests that\n\u00ab\u00dc13 ic}tlng democrats will not at\n\u00abjtend the coming state convent'on,\nhut with this defeat rankling ltt\ntheir breasts It seems more conserva\ntlvs to believe that the Wallace con\nvention will see a renewal of the\nfight which opened a wide schism at\nTwin Palls. Meanwhile Dubo's Is\nth\u00ab victor, hnd hla policies triumph.\nPROSPECT ING OK RESULTS.\nWith the latest returns Pendleton\nnnd Umatilla county go dry without\nquestion. July 1, If the law be obey\ned. there will be no saloons in the\ncounty and no liquor sold. It is the\nwill of the majority expressed at the\npolls Monday.\nThat there will be financial losses\nto some and business depression in\ncertain lines temporarily is inevita\nble. But such depressions will be\npurely temporary. Umatilla county\nI\u00ab too far advanced to be affected\nseriously by the cuting off of the\nliquor traffic and its dependent busi\nnesses. Pendleton business men are\ntoo firmly entrenched to suffer from\nthe pessimistic cries of those who\n.ra\nThe Light\nThat's Bright\nUnder tbs glittering\nifeht of ths else trio\n\u2022C\nlamp, every\nUtnc is\nnt Its bsst A\npoorly-furnished boos*\n\u00ab\u00bbnames bright sad\nch ee r ful in app\u00e9nmnes\nwith the introduction\nof nleetrle lighL\nTh* dark nnd dingy\nstore onoe avoided\nby shoppers, quickly\nshangeo its character\nand b eo on oo a buoy\n\u25a0art of trad* ander\nth* radiant brilllnnos\nof Blnotrie Illumina\nat Electric\nOffice\nCaA\nLicht\n<:Ol\n;unji\nmust turn to other lines of trade,\noi who may lose, at the beginning, a\nfew hundred dollars in patronage.\nThe commercial level Is bound to\ncontinue; the financial conditions In\nthis city and county cannot be upset.\nFor these reasons the Tribune, 1\ndoes not take the gloomy view of the\nbusiness outlook that some of the\nlocal merchants do. The loss of rev\nenue to the city apd county may be\nmade up In other ways; It may be\nmore than true\u2014let us hope It\u2014\nthat tjje claim of the local option\npeople that savings to the working\nmen will more than replace those\nmunicipal revenues. Either way,\nnow that the conditions have been\ngiven us, let us go in and give them,\na fair trial\u2014do our best to keep j\nPendleton and Umatilla county\nthe upward grade\u2014try out local op\ntion from a business standpoint\u2014\nand if It fails, turn to another plan.\nIf it succed8, stick to It.\u2014Pendleton\nTribune.\nTHE OPIUM CURSE.\nMr. Root, the secretary of state,\nbas asked congress for an appropria\ntion of $20,000 with which to or\nganize a commlss'on of three mem\nbers and a secretary to make a thor\nough investigation of the opium evil.\nNext January a conference is to be\nheld In Shanghai, China, interna\ntional in character, to discuss plans\nfor the nradtcat'on of the curse, i\nPresident Roosevelt has Indorsed the\nmovement.\nThis crusade la hut one evidence]\nof the great activity manifested in\nall countries against a curse that iaj\nscarcely second to the liquor evil in i\nits deadly results. While the opium I\nhabit has not obtained so firm a hold\nit; the United States, its use, partie- j\nularly in the large cities. Is becom\ning more common every year and it!\nwill soon be a matter demanding at- j\nU-ntlon here, Just as it claims the\nconsideration In all the countries of,\nEurope and Asia. England has tak*\nen hold of the matter vigorously and j\nwill stop the practice of licensing i\nopium resorts in her far Eastern I\npossessions.\n\n\nTHINK IT OVER.\n\n\n\n\u2666\u2666\u2666\u2666\u2666\u2666\u2666\u26664\nI\nThe trouble about the factions in,\nthe democratic party in Idaho Is\nthat you cannot tell which is the tall\nand which Is the dog.\nI\nSenator Heltfeld, who was left at\nhome, will probably be seated in thejp\nnationa! convention. What was des-|\nignated for a toboggan was really a\nthrough train. j\nft\nSpeaking of the par/lng of Du\nhols. It is only given to a few of\nthe elect to sit on the fence and see\nhim go by.\n\nThe senatorial situation now In j\nOregon Is merely n question of\nstanding pat.\n\nIf this prohibition wave keens ris\ning, what will become Of the schoon\ners that bump on till bar.\n\nA special meeting of the Royal\nNelghbors is called for tonight at.\nWoodman hall. A full attendance I\nCOMING EVENTS.\n\nis desired, as the matter of organ\nIztng a degree team will be consid\nered.\nft ft\nThe city council will meet tonight\nfor the transaction of general busi\nness.\n\nThe annual rose fair, conducted\nunder the auspices of the ladles of\nthe Presbyterian church has been\npostponed until Saturday. June 13.\n\nThe annual picnic of the Presby\nterian Sunday school will he held\nTuesday at Joseph. Two extra\ncoaches will be added to the regular\nmorning train leaving the city at 7\no'clock.\nft\nThe R. B. Hayes post of the W. R.\nC. will meet at 2 o'clock Friday aft\nernoon at the home of MaJ. Manning.\nThis will be the last meetiug before\nthe summer vacation.\nBANKS MUST NOW PAY INTER\nEST ON DEPOSITS.\nNew Currency Law Makes It Obliga\ntory to Pay 1 Per Cent to\nthe Government.\n\nWASHINGTON, June 5.\u2014Under\nthe terms of the new currency law\npassed by congress in the closing\nhours of the last session, banks in\nwhich funds of the government are\ndeposited must hereafter pay inter\nest for the use of such funds. An\nexception Is made in the case of\nthose banking associations designat\ned as national depositories, in which\nfunds are' placed strictly for the use\nof the government's own expe 8\nThere are outstanding about *72,\n000.000 of government fund\u00bb on\njwhtch interest must he paid by\n__________\nbanks, nnd by nn odd coincidence a\nsimilar amount resta In depoeltoryjfc^^\nlOCi;\nbanks not subject to the tax. It was\nstated at the treasury department\nyesterday that not only would the\nlew be charged on all deposits of\ngovernment money made In the fu\nture, but that the tax would be\npayable on funds already deposited\nit. banks, from the time the new\nlaw became effective. The rate of\ninterest chargeable is to be not less\nthan 1 per cent, and as much more\nas the secretary of the treasury\nmay deem proper.\nFor the present, however, the rate\not Interest will probably be 1 per\ncent per annum.\nIn the South and the West each\nyear huge sums of money are neces\nsary to move the crops, and govern\nment funds have frequently aided\non'greatly in relieving the situation.\nDuring the recent stringency there\nwas a cry for government funds from\nthe crop centers. Hereafter banks\nmust pay for money loaned by the\ngovernment to move crops.\nIn the banks designated as regu\nlar depositories the government de\nposits fiinds to carry on necessary\nexpenses of the government in vari\nous parts of the country. The gov\nernment is benefited by lending thej\nand in many)\ncases, it is said, the banks are not 1\nonly not anx'ous to be depositories!\nof government funds, but have asked\nto he excused from acting as deposi\nbanks this money\ntories.\nThere has. therefore been no tax\nP ,a< ed u I ,on these \u00bb'egular deposits.\n\nOdd Fellows, Attention,\nAll members of Gateway and No.\ng, all members of Clearwater En-\ncampment No. 7 and all members!\nof Alpha Rebekah Lodge No. 1 are\nrequested to meet in the Odd Fel\nlows' hall on Main street at 3 o'clock\np. rn., Sunday, June 7, for the due\nobservance of the I. O. O. F memo\nrial service.\nit is especially requested that you\nbring flowers for decorating at the\ncemetery'. COMMITTEE.\n1\nAx EXPERIENCE BOOKKEEPER\nand general office man wants situ\nation of any kind. Address Lock\nbox 237, Clarkston.\nSummer Tourist Travel Begins.\nThe travel to the Eastern states\nfor summer vacations has commenc\ned, the flr6t party leaving Lewiston\nthis morning routed over the O. R.\nx. company's lines. The party con\ngists of Mr. and Mrs. Frost of\nClarkston, St. Paul; Miss Williams,\nIowa; Miss Bronson, Iowa; Miss\nChriss Shendel, Minnesota; Miss\na t c hen, Iowa; Miss Elizabeth Ket\ntenbach, Chicago; Miss Grace Har\nwick, Chicago; Mrs. William Clem\nenson, Chicago; Miss Marie Long,\n.Minesota, and Miss Beckley, Iowa.\nCOUNTY RECORDS IN BAD SHAPE\nDistrict Judge Wood Criticizes the\nKootenai System.\nSANDPOINT, Ida., June 5 \u2014\"To\nmy positive knowledge public rec\nords are stored in a woodshed at\nRathdrum,\" declared District Judge\nW. W. Woods yesterday from the\nbench. He went on to state that\nnever in his 40 years of practice had\nhe seen an equal to the Rathdrum\nsystem and the way that public doc\numents were cared for.\nThis occurred in the case of\nSlankard against the Hope Lumber\nCo., which has been heard in the dis\ntrict court for three days. The at\nt orne y 8 f or Slankard desired td in\ntroduce as evidence the testimony of\ngi an ijard in a former trial, which\nwas held at Rathdrum three years\nago, and as Slankard was without\nthe jurisdiction of the court they\nwere given permission to do so.\nThen commenced the hunt for the\nmissing record, and the lawyers for\nSlankard thought they had the evi\ndence when they went into court\nyesterday morning, but it was defec\ntive and was not allowed.\nAfter Judge Wood had refused to\nallow the record to be Introduced he\ndelivered his opinion of the care of\nthe records at the Kootenai court\nhouse.\nREMAINS BROUGHT HERE TODAY\nVictim of Railroad Accident Has a\nBrother in Winnipeg.\nThe remain^ of Joseph Hader, the\nrailroad employe killed on the Lew\nIston-Rlparla line last night, were\nbrought to Lewiston this afternoon\nand taken to the Vassar undertaking\nparlors to be prepared for burial.\nHader was about 24 years of age\nand has a brother residing at Winnl\npeg. Members of the train crew with\nwhom he was working state he was\ns'tting on the end of a box car and\nleaning acroes to the car behind. As\nthe train struck a curve the space\nbetween th\u00ab cars was widened and\nthe unfortunate man dropped to the\ntrack and was killed Instantly be\nneath the car wheels.\nThe funeral arrangements will not\nhe made until a message from the\nbrother has been received.\nDano* at Bradford hall. Clarks\nton, every Friday evening.\nWallet and Coffee for breakfast\nat the Dairy\u2014Rut fine.\nUte the new Tungsten Lama a\ng fO per %\u00c9at Lewis to*\ngiggly Co* aka \u00abffafe\nt\u00ab.-<\nheist t\n55\nPairs of\nShoes and\nOxfords\n$2.95\nTo closeout at\nPer pair. Just a lot of $4.00 to $6.00 Shoes we are offering re\ngardless of first cost.\nYou will save money to b ay.\ntyfatson Clothing Co.\nThe Best Is\nNone Too Good\nThat's my motto, and any work done by this shop must come\nup to the motto.\nSteam and Hot Water Heating, Gas Fitting. Special atten\ntion to Sewer Connection Work. Get our figures before letting\nany contract Repair work promptly attended to.\nCHAS. NORUN, PLUMBER\n807 Main St.\nOffice Phone. Main 34 Residence. Red 1091. _\nJ. W. MULLINIX'S\nELECTRIC INSTITUTE AND\nSANITARIUM.\nNew Light Cure. All Forms of\nHydriatic Treatment. Electric,\nHot Air and Turkish Baths. Lat\nest improved equipment. Lady\nassistant.\nComer Third and Main Streets.\nPhone Black 611.\nLEW1SK0N, IDAHO.\n\u00dftate Qt Ohio, City oi Toledo, Lucas\nCounty, sa,\nFrank J. Ch\u00e9ney makes oath that\nhe Is senior partner of the firm of\nF. J. Cheney ft Co., doing busineas\nin the City of Toledo, County and\nState afforesald, and that said firm\nwill pay the sum of ONE HUNDRED\nDOLLARS for each and every case\nof Catarrh that cannot be cured by\nthe use of Hall's Catarrh Cure.\nFRANK J, CHENEY.\nSworn to before me und subscrib\ned in my presence this 6th day of\nDecember, A. D. 1886.\n(8eal) A. W. GLEASON,\nNotary Publie.\nHall's Catarrh Cure is taken in\nternally, nnd acts directly on the\nblood nnd mueonc surfaces of the\nsystem, \u00abend far testimonials, free\nF. J. CHENEY ft OO..\nToledo, O.\nSold by all Drugg